-<div id="s6" class="section">
-  <div class="section-header">
-    <span class="section-number">Section 06</span>
-    <h2>The Convergence Thesis: Bidirectional Failure</h2>
-  </div>
-
-  <p>Across Kit A and the diagnostic domains studied so far, the identical underlying pattern emerged. A solo frontier model, operating alone, completed its assigned task perfectly and still delivered the wrong verdict because it answered the narrow question it was asked.</p>
-
-  <p>The benchmark results reinforce this structural limitation. It is not primarily a problem of raw model intelligence. It is a problem of isolated inference operating without adversarial pressure at the final irreversible step. A more powerful model simply processes a flawed operational frame with greater efficiency and confidence.</p>
-
-  <p>The deployment risk is not just model selection. It is decision architecture. Adding more agents is not the same as adding governed adjudication. A notable diagnostic finding (ATLAS-2026-001) showed that ungoverned multi-agent councils can introduce failure modes not observed in solo review. Under consensus pressure, a homogeneous council induced an Evidence Checker role to literally invent support from a primary document. Multi-agent review is not automatically equivalent to governed adjudication.</p>
-</div>
-
-<!-- SECTION 7 -->
-<div id="s7" class="section">
-  <div class="section-header">
-    <span class="section-number">Section 07</span>
-    <h2>Why Human Review Alone Is Not Enough</h2>
-  </div>
-
-  <p>Human-in-the-loop oversight is the industry&#8217;s default answer to AI safety. While necessary in some workflows, it fails as a scalable architecture for autonomous operations.</p>
-  <p>The issue is not human intelligence; it is human review conditions. While AI systems pull data and generate intents at machine speed, human reviewers are routinely forced to operate under severe time constraints, staring at fragmented notification windows without the underlying data graph needed to verify the context. This transforms human review into a stressful operational bottleneck and a rubber-stamp liability layer.</p>
-  <p>Humans are structurally unsuited to maintaining uninterrupted, hyper-vigilant scrutiny over thousands of clean-looking data lines at machine speed. They experience fatigue, accept plausible explanations too easily, and suffer from automation bias.</p>
-  <div class="pullquote">The ultimate promise of enterprise AI is not faster queues for humans to watch; it is <strong>trusted delegation</strong> &#8212; the ability to hand a high-consequence workflow to a system with total confidence because the safety checkpoint is embedded in the architecture itself.</div>
-  <p>Because current policy layers lack deep evidentiary interrogation, they default to dumping the final decision on a human. But human reviewers operating under severe time constraints, staring at fragmented notification windows, quickly become fatigued. This transforms human review into a stressful operational bottleneck and a rubber-stamp liability. Holo&#8217;s adversarial council and Governor are designed to deliver that required evidence-based scrutiny at machine speed.</p>
-</div>
-
-<!-- SECTION 8 -->
-<div id="s8" class="section">
-  <div class="section-header">
-    <span class="section-number">Section 08</span>
-    <h2>Objections</h2>
-  </div>
-
-  <div class="objection">
-    <h3>&#8220;But we already have strong policy layers, guardrails, and control planes.&#8221;</h3>
-    <p>These tools are necessary and incredibly valuable for establishing baseline security. However, organizations with mature policy layers and risk frameworks in place still fail at the action boundary &#8212; because policy layers check identity and permissions, not whether the specific action in front of the system is structurally sound.</p>
-    <p>A policy layer is the passport check at the gate. Holo does not replace that Layer 1 foundation. It adds the missing Layer 2. This is the deep, evidence-based interrogation right at the action boundary, the exact moment when an agent wants to execute something irreversible.</p>
-  </div>
-
-  <div class="objection">
-    <h3>&#8220;This is a vendor-built benchmark.&#8221;</h3>
-    <p>Yes. The same team designed the scenarios and engineered the system. To control for this bias, Holo uses identical frontier models inside its engine room as those tested in the solo baselines. Holo is not beating old or weak models; it is proving that orchestrating those exact same models inside an adversarial framework yields a completely different decision outcome.</p>
-  </div>
-
-  <div class="objection">
-    <h3>&#8220;The sample size is too small.&#8221;</h3>
-    <p>Correct. The completed Kit A evidence and diagnostic domain work do not provide a universal census of AI behavior. The paper separates benchmark-locked evidence from diagnostic findings and retired candidates for exactly this reason.</p>
-  </div>
-
-  <div class="objection">
-    <h3>&#8220;Models are getting smarter. The problem will fix itself.&#8221;</h3>
-    <p>Model updates are symmetric, and advancements are equally available to adversaries. Furthermore, increased model intelligence does not fix structural alignment gaps like <em>Procedural Obedience</em>. A more capable model simply processes a flawed operational frame with greater efficiency.</p>
-  </div>
-</div>
-
-<!-- SECTION 9 -->
-<div id="s9" class="section">
-  <div class="section-header">
-    <span class="section-number">Section 09</span>
-    <h2>What This Paper Does Not Claim</h2>
-  </div>
-
-  <ul style="margin:1rem 0 1rem 1.5rem;font-size:0.975rem;color:var(--ink-muted);line-height:1.9">
-    <li><strong>We do not claim independent third-party validation.</strong> This is an internal research paper with public, reproducible baselines.</li>
-    <li><strong>We do not claim production reliability metrics.</strong> Performance under live enterprise transaction flows will vary based on data engineering quality.</li>
-    <li><strong>We do not claim Holo replaces traditional security.</strong> Firewalls, identity access management, and logging are still required to handle known infrastructure parameters. Holo exists solely to adjudicate the unresolved semantic middle.</li>
-    <li><strong>We do not claim that regression results are new benchmark wins.</strong> Regression validates repairs on known frozen packets; benchmark credit requires fresh frozen packets and Judge adjudication.</li>
-    <li><strong>We do not claim Domain 8 is a completed formal kit.</strong> Domain 8 remains diagnostic complete / formal locked kit pending.</li>
-    <li><strong>We do not claim Holo catches everything.</strong> Holo&#8217;s lifecycle exposes both model failures and Holo&#8217;s own runtime failures.</li>
-  </ul>
-</div>
-
-<!-- SECTION 10 -->
-<div id="s10" class="section">
-  <div class="section-header">
-    <span class="section-number">Section 10</span>
-    <h2>What Comes Next</h2>
-  </div>
-
-  <p>Holo maintains a Blindspot Atlas to preserve lessons from benchmark-locked cases, diagnostic runs, failed hypotheses, and architecture-sensitive failures. The Atlas is not a marketing scoreboard. It is a failure-surface memory layer.</p>
-  <p>For example, not every hypothesized blindspot survives testing. A Fund Ops period-scope seam (ATLAS-2026-002) was rejected after testing because frontier models reliably detected the explicit conflict between a mid-quarter acquisition date and a full-quarter trial balance. Holo records these negative findings rather than promoting them as wins.</p>
-  <p>Domain 8 remains diagnostic complete / formal locked kit pending. Recent PE sibling work reinforced the packet-lifecycle standard: an ALLOW packet must contain the primary approval object, explicit gate closure, and all referenced attachments. Candidates that fail those standards are retired or held as diagnostic, not counted as benchmark evidence.</p>
